            <h4><i class="fas fa-exclamation-circle"></i> The Cost of Errors</h4>
            <p>"Shall" vs "may" changes obligation to permission. A mistranslated deadline can miss a filing. Inconsistent names raise fraud concerns.</p>
          </div>

          <p>Our translators know both languages AND UAE law. They understand:</p>
          
          <ul class="legal-expertise">
            <li><i class="fas fa-balance-scale"></i> <a href="/locations/dubai/">Dubai Courts</a> civil law terminology</li>
            <li><i class="fas fa-landmark"></i> <a href="/locations/dubai/difc/">DIFC</a> common law conventions</li>
            <li><i class="fas fa-file-contract"></i> <a href="/legal/contracts/">Contract</a> drafting standards</li>
            <li><i class="fas fa-link"></i> Cross-reference alignment</li>
          </ul>

          <h3>Court Document Translation</h3>

          <p>UAE courts need Arabic for all proceedings. No exceptions.</p>

          <p><strong>What we translate for courts:</strong></p>
          <ul class="simple-list">
            <li>Foreign judgments (for recognition)</li>
            <li>Evidence bundles and exhibits</li>
            <li>Witness statements</li>
            <li>Expert reports</li>
            <li>Documentary evidence</li>
          </ul>

